What is a Protocol?

A protocol is a set of rules that define how data is transmitted and communicated between devices over a network.

HTTP / HTTPS ‚Üí Used for web communication
TCP ‚Üí Ensures reliable data delivery
UDP ‚Üí Faster but no guarantee of delivery
FTP ‚Üí Used for file transfer
SMTP ‚Üí Used for sending emails

-  While transferring file via mail There are 2 protocols 1 is SMTP other is ftp
-  to avoid conflict we use port 25 for SMTP and 20 for ftp
-

HTTPS secures communication between the client and server by using SSL/TLS encryption. It encrypts the data before transmission so that even if an attacker intercepts the traffic, they cannot read or modify the information.‚Äù

How it works (Simple Explanation):

1Ô∏è‚É£ Client sends request to server (HTTPS)
2Ô∏è‚É£ Server sends its SSL/TLS certificate
3Ô∏è‚É£ Secure session key is generated
4Ô∏è‚É£ Data is encrypted before transmission
5Ô∏è‚É£ Only the intended server can decrypt it

Https ensures cia triad

Difference Between HTTPS and TLS
üîπ TLS (Transport Layer Security)
TLS is a cryptographic protocol.
It provides encryption, integrity, and authentication.
It can secure different protocols (HTTPS, FTPS, SMTPS, etc.).
Works at the transport layer.
üëâ TLS = Security technology (encryption mechanism)

HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure)
HTTPS is HTTP + TLS.
It is used specifically for secure web communication.
It runs over port 443.
Used in websites to protect user data.
üëâ HTTPS = Application protocol that uses TLS for security

