Difference Between TCP and UDP
üîπ TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)
Connection-oriented
Reliable (guarantees delivery)
Data comes in correct order
Error checking and retransmission
Slower than UDP

üìå Used in:
HTTP / HTTPS ,FTP ,Email ,SSH

UDP (User Datagram Protocol)
Connectionless
No guarantee of delivery
No ordering of packets
No retransmission
Faster than TCP

üìå Used in:
Video streaming
Online gaming
VoIP
DNS

7 OSI Layers (Top to Bottom)
7Ô∏è‚É£ Application Layer

User interacts here

Protocols: HTTP, FTP, SMTP, DNS
üëâ Example: Opening a website

6Ô∏è‚É£ Presentation Layer

Encryption / Decryption

Data formatting
üëâ Example: HTTPS encryption

5Ô∏è‚É£ Session Layer

Establishes and manages sessions
üëâ Example: Login session
Transport Layer

End-to-end communication

TCP / UDP
üëâ Ensures data delivery

3Ô∏è‚É£ Network Layer

IP addressing and routing
üëâ Routers work here

2Ô∏è‚É£ Data Link Layer

MAC address

Switch works here

1Ô∏è‚É£ Physical Layer

Cables, signals, hardware
üëâ Actual data transmission
